Presentation of the Topic and Contextualization

Air Quality Index (AQI)

An Air Quality Index (AQI) is utilized to communicate the current level of air pollution to the general public, as well as forecast future pollution levels. To measure it, we measure multiple components, that are provided in this dataset. The problem, of course, is that the AQI is not good in every region of the world, and nowadays news keep us thinking that it is never going to be improved at our rate. By studying this dataset, we wand to show that it is possible to reduce the global impact by pollutants by decentralizing ourselves from the city. Of course, all of this is pretty theoritical, and our main manoeuvre here is to target the AQI to see if we can predict it with less components, we will talk about that in the Description of the problem. This dataset also provides geolocated information about the following pollutants:

Nitrogen Dioxide [NO2]

Nitrogen Dioxide is one of several nitrogen oxides. It enters the air through natural phenomena, such as stratospheric entry or lightning. However, at ground level, NO2 primarily forms from emissions of cars, trucks, buses, power plants, and off-road equipment. Short-term exposure can worsen respiratory diseases, such as asthma, while longer exposures may contribute to the development of asthma and respiratory infections. People with asthma, children, and the elderly are at higher risk of NO2-related health effects.

Ozone [O3]

The Ozone molecule is harmful for outdoor air quality (if outside of the ozone layer). At ground level, ozone is created through chemical reactions between nitrogen oxides and volatile organic compounds (VOCs). Unlike the beneficial ozone found in the upper atmosphere, ground-level ozone can cause a range of health problems, including chest pain, coughing, throat irritation, and airway inflammation. It can also reduce lung function and worsen conditions like bronchitis, emphysema, and asthma. Additionally, ozone negatively affects vegetation and ecosystems, particularly by damaging sensitive plants during the growing season.

Carbon Monoxide [CO]

Carbon Monoxide is a colorless and odorless gas. It is primarily emitted into the outdoor air by cars, trucks, and other vehicles or machinery that burn fossil fuels. Indoor sources of CO include kerosene and gas space heaters, as well as gas stoves, which can degrade indoor air quality. Breathing air with high concentrations of CO reduces the amount of oxygen that can be transported in the bloodstream to critical organs like the heart and brain. At very high levels, which are unlikely to occur outdoors but possible in enclosed environments, CO can cause dizziness, confusion, unconsciousness, and even death.

Particulate Matter [PM2.5]

Atmospheric Particulate Matter, also known as atmospheric aerosol particles, is a complex mixture of small solid and liquid matter that becomes suspended in the air. When inhaled, these particles can cause serious heart and lung problems. They have been classified as group 1 carcinogens by the International Agency for Research on Cancer (IARC). PM10 refers to particles with a diameter of 10 micrometers or less, while PM2.5 refers to particles with a diameter of 2.5 micrometers or less.

Description and Formalization of the Problem

"What you can't measure is what you can't improve" - Kelvin

There is a problem about AQI measures, and we will try to provide solutions to them. First, the problem we will try to solve is the cost of measurement, then, we will talk about the covering space of these measures. To keep introducing our subject, we will then observe the dataset provided and enounce our overview on it.

Cost of the Measurement

Getting the AQI values of areas of the world can be an interesting measurement, because it could be helpful to know where we could build pollutant spaces without turning the air toxic or unbreathable. On the other hand, there are also areas that are simply naturally polluted and can't be used to be built on (i.e: obviously a volcano is not the perfect site to build a city, but there are less noticable areas that are naturally enticed to pollution). The problem is that getting the AQI value is requiring the measurement of four different pollutants, and each of them has a different scientific protocol to measure it. These protocols cost a lot: sometimes we talk about tens of thousands of dollars for on pollutant. Our study has the objective to find out if there are pollutants that share a bigger part in the AQI value, and if we could get rid of the others that necessitate big sums of money. Also, we will focus on the components that can be measured with the same means, so that one stone will kill two birds.

Impact on the World Crisis

With lower measurement cost, it could be easily envisageable to cover more ground and have a bigger overview of the world's AQI. Even though it is not one of the most important criteria companies and countries look over when they want to build, we tend in a world where breathable air will become central (i.e: in China, they pay to breath neutral air with a price per minute). For countries that have big unexploited spaces (like France: La diagonale du vide), it might be a new criteria, and a lower cost of measurement will make it more accessible.

def make_basic_overview(data):
    border = 12*'='
    
    print(border, 'Basic Info', border)
    data.info()
    print('\n\n')
    
    print(border, 'First Five Rows', border)
    display(data.head())
    print('\n\n')
    
    print(border, 'Last Five Rows', border)
    display(data.tail())
    print('\n\n')
    
    print(border, 'Duplicates', border)
    print()
    if data.duplicated().sum() > 0:
        print(f'Amount of duplicated rows: {data.duplicated().sum()}.')
        data.drop_duplicates(inplace=True, ignore_index=True)
        print('Duplicated rows were dropped.')
    else:
        print('None.')

def make_df_dtype(data):
    cols, dtype_col, specimens, nunique, null_share = [], [], [], [], []
    for column in data:
        cols.append(column)
        
        this_dtype = data[column].dtype
        dtype_col.append(this_dtype)
        
        specimen = data.loc[data[column].first_valid_index(), column]
        specimens.append(specimen)
        
        nunique.append(data[column].nunique())
        
        null_sum = data[column].isna().sum()
        null_to_len = null_sum / len(data[column])
        null_share.append(f'{null_to_len:.2%}')
        
    df = pd.DataFrame(list(zip(dtype_col,
                               specimens,
                               nunique,
                              null_share)),
                      index=cols)    
    df.columns=['dtype',
                'specimen',
                'nunique',
               'null_share']
 
    return df

    data[cols].hist(bins=30, figsize=(width, height))

def make_heatmap_cities_per_countries_and_categories(
    data,
    list_of_countries,
    category_column,
    ylabel,
    xlabel,
    plttitle,
    palette
):
    df = data[data['country'].isin(list_of_countries)].copy()
    
    category_order = ['Good', 'Moderate', 'Unhealthy for Sensitive Groups', 'Unhealthy', 'Very Unhealthy', 'Hazardous']
    df[category_column] = pd.Categorical(df[category_column], categories=category_order, ordered=True)
    
    this_crosstab = pd.crosstab(
        index=df['country'],
        columns=df[category_column],
        values=df['city'],
        aggfunc='count',
        normalize='index'
    )
    
    #Heatmap
    sns.heatmap(
        this_crosstab.sort_values(by='Good', ascending=False),
        cmap=palette,
        annot=True,
        fmt='.2%',
        linecolor='#959595',
        linewidths=.75,
        cbar=False
    )
    plt.ylabel(ylabel)
    plt.xlabel(xlabel)
    plt.xticks(rotation=45, ha='right')
    plt.title(plttitle, fontsize=25, loc='left')
    plt.show()

Solutions and choices of the Machine Learning Algorithms


Clustering Problem : find the class of the AQI

Decision Trees and Logistic Regression are chosen because they are classification algorithms that offer transparency, efficiency, and the ability to handle both numerical and categorical data with interpretability. In contrast, HDBSCAN and K-Means are clustering algorithms better suited for exploratory data analysis to find natural groupings within data rather than for classifying data points into predefined categories. Hence, we prefer to use Decision Tree and Logistic Regression for our study.

Regression study : predict the exact value of AQI

For our study we decided to try : Linear Regression, Ridge Regression, Lasso Regression, Decision Tree Regressor, Random Forest Regressor, Gradient Boosting Regressor. For our specific study we believe that a subset of features is important => Lasso regression should perform well. We have a complex and non linear realationships => Decision Tree Regressor, Random Forest and Gradient Boosting should perform well. We set up these choices and try to get the best results we can.

def kfoldCrossValidation(X, y, M, k):
    X = np.array(X)
    y = np.array(y)

    kfold = KFold(n_splits=k, shuffle=True, random_state=42)
    scores = []

    for train_index, test_index in kfold.split(X):
        X_train, X_test = X[train_index], X[test_index]
        y_train, y_test = y[train_index], y[test_index]

        M.fit(X_train, y_train)
        y_pred = M.predict(X_test)
        accuracy = accuracy_score(y_test, y_pred)
        scores.append(accuracy)

    return scores

def average_accuracy(scores):
    return sum(scores) / len(scores)

gini = DecisionTreeClassifier(max_depth=2, criterion='gini')
gini.fit(X_train, y_train)
impurities = gini.tree_.impurity
children_left = gini.tree_.children_left
children_right = gini.tree_.children_right

is_leaf = np.logical_and(children_left == -1, children_right == -1)
node_impurities = impurities[~is_leaf]
most_impure_node = np.argmax(node_impurities)

children_left[most_impure_node] = -1
children_right[most_impure_node] = -1

node_indices = gini.apply(X_train)
samples_most_impure_node = X_train[node_indices == most_impure_node]

For the PM2.5 AQI Value, we notice that the density of cluster 0 for PM2.5 is around 50, whereas the density for cluster 1 is around 170, as illustrated in the means printed above. Additionally, the Ozone mean value is twice as great in cluster 1 than in cluster 0.

Conclusion:
We can say that there are fewer countries with high AQI values, and these can be distinguished by higher values in pollutants like PM2.5 or Ozone. However, the CO value does not seem to be a definitive separating criterion between clusters.

labels = ['Good', 'Hazardous', 'Moderate', 'Unhealthy', 'Unhealthy for Sensitive Groups', 'Very Unhealthy', 'accuracy']
decision_tree_metrics = [1.00, 0.00, 1.00, 0.80, 0.91, 0.00, 0.97]
logistic_regression_metrics = [0.97, 0.97, 0.93, 0.88, 0.94, 0.77, 0.94]

x = np.arange(len(labels))
width = 0.35

fig, ax = plt.subplots()
rects1 = ax.bar(x - width/2, decision_tree_metrics, width, label='Decision Tree')
rects2 = ax.bar(x + width/2, logistic_regression_metrics, width, label='Logistic Regression')

ax.set_ylabel('Scores')
ax.set_title('Scores by model and class')
ax.set_xticks(x)
ax.set_xticklabels(labels, rotation=45)
ax.legend()

ax.bar_label(rects1, padding=3)
ax.bar_label(rects2, padding=3)

fig.tight_layout()

plt.show()

Observations:

Decision Tree Evaluation:

  • High accuracy (97%) with perfect precision and recall for 'Good' and 'Moderate' categories.
  • Good performance on 'Unhealthy for Sensitive Groups' category (precision: 0.91, recall: 1.00).
  • Poor performance on 'Hazardous' and 'Very Unhealthy' categories, failing to correctly classify any instances.
  • Overall, the model excels in some categories but completely fails in others, suggesting it might be overfitting to certain classes.

Logistic Regression Evaluation:

  • Slightly lower overall accuracy (94%) but more balanced performance across categories.
  • Better performance in 'Hazardous' and 'Very Unhealthy' categories compared to the Decision Tree, indicating an ability to handle minority classes better.
  • High precision and recall for 'Good' and 'Moderate' categories, though slightly lower than the Decision Tree.
  • Demonstrates a more consistent performance across different categories.

Conclusion:

  • While the Decision Tree has a higher overall accuracy, its performance is highly skewed towards certain categories, completely failing to classify some classes. This could be a sign of overfitting to the majority classes. In contrast, the Logistic Regression model shows a more balanced performance, effectively classifying minority classes as well.
  • Given the importance of accurately classifying all categories in air quality index prediction, especially the 'Hazardous' and 'Very Unhealthy' categories for public health implications, the Logistic Regression model is a more suitable choice. Its ability to more uniformly classify across all categories makes it a more reliable model for practical applications in this context.

    models = [
    ("Linear Regression", LinearRegression()),
    ("Ridge Regression", Ridge()),
    ("Lasso Regression", Lasso()),
    ("Decision Tree", DecisionTreeRegressor(random_state=42)),
    ("Random Forest", RandomForestRegressor(random_state=42)),
    ("Gradient Boosting", GradientBoostingRegressor(random_state=42)),
]
# dictionnaires pour stocker les performances et les importances des features
model_performance = {}
feature_importance_dict = {}

for name, model in models:
    model.fit(X_train, y_train)
    y_pred = model.predict(X_test)
    
    rmse = np.sqrt(mean_squared_error(y_test, y_pred))
    
    model_performance[name] = rmse
    
    # to get the most importants variables it depends on the model
    if name in ["Linear Regression", "Ridge Regression", "Lasso Regression"]:
        importance = model.coef_
    else:
        importance = model.feature_importances_
    feature_importance = pd.DataFrame(importance, index=X_train.columns, columns=["Importance"])
    feature_importance = feature_importance.sort_values("Importance", ascending=False)
    feature_importance_dict[name] = feature_importance

model_performance_df = pd.DataFrame(list(model_performance.items()), columns=['Model', 'RMSE'])
print(model_performance_df)
for name, importance in feature_importance_dict.items():
    print(f"Importance des features pour {name}:")
    print(importance.head(10))
    print("\n")

    Observations:

    RMSE Analysis:
    RMSE is a measure of the differences between values predicted by a model and the values observed. The lower the RMSE, the better the model's performance.

    • Linear Regression and Ridge Regression have similar performance with the highest RMSE, suggesting underfitting in complex, non-linear relationships.
    • Lasso Regression shows a slightly lower RMSE, indicating its intrinsic feature selection might be aiding its performance.
    • Decision Tree Regressor exhibits a marked improvement, supporting the dataset's non-linear nature.
    • Random Forest Regressor further reduces RMSE, demonstrating the effectiveness of an ensemble approach.
    • Gradient Boosting Regressor has the lowest RMSE, suggesting it's the most effective at modeling the data and making predictions for AQI.

    Relation to Initial Suppositions:
    Lasso Regression's performance partially confirms the importance of feature selection. The hypothesis that non-linear models would perform better is strongly confirmed, with Decision Tree, Random Forest, and Gradient Boosting outperforming linear models.

    Conclusion:
    Considering RMSE values, the Gradient Boosting Regressor emerges as the best model for predicting AQI, effectively handling non-linear relationships and outperforming other models, including Lasso Regression.

    from sklearn.model_selection import GridSearchCV
from sklearn.ensemble import RandomForestRegressor
from sklearn.metrics import make_scorer, mean_squared_error
import numpy as np

param_grid = {
    'n_estimators': [30, 40, 50],  # Number of trees in the forest
    'max_depth': [None, 2, 3, 10],  # Maximum depth of the tree
    'min_samples_split': [1, 2, 3, 5, 10],  # Minimum number of samples required to split a node
    'min_samples_leaf': [1, 2, 3, 4],    # Minimum number of samples required at each leaf node
    'bootstrap': [True, False]        # Method of selecting samples for training each tree
}

rf = RandomForestRegressor(random_state=42)
scorer = make_scorer(mean_squared_error, greater_is_better=False)
grid_search = GridSearchCV(estimator=rf, param_grid=param_grid, cv=3, n_jobs=-1, verbose=2)

grid_search.fit(X_train, y_train)
best_params = grid_search.best_params_
print(f"Best parameters: {best_params}")
best_rf = grid_search.best_estimator_
y_pred_best = best_rf.predict(X_test)

rmse_best = np.sqrt(mean_squared_error(y_test, y_pred_best))
print(f"RMSE of the best model: {rmse_best}")

    Fitting 3 folds for each of 480 candidates, totalling 1440 fits
Best parameters: {'bootstrap': True, 'max_depth': None, 'min_samples_leaf': 2, 'min_samples_split': 2, 'n_estimators': 50}
RMSE of the best model: 2.775730360917432

    Observations:

    Our grid search covers a wide range of parameters, and despite its extensive nature, we found that no parameter combination reduced the RMSE more effectively than the default settings of the RandomForestRegressor. This outcome is not unusual as the default settings in RandomForest are typically well-suited for a variety of data types. It's possible that our grid search did not encompass the optimal settings for our specific dataset, or the model might have become too complex, affecting its performaata.
